The food is delicious and fresh and great portion sizes for the price. Wonderful location and atmosphere. The staff are very kind and hard working and bring a feeling of home-like comfort and a lot of fun during these hard times. William and Loris are such a great team. Come for the food, stay for them.  10/10 would recommend. Very happy costumer and definitely will be returning!

Went there for brunch.. Loris was our server and he was amazing! Friendly, hospitable and truly made us feel like family. The food was also great! We had a small feast for 3 people that included the burrata (although I wish it was on some greens vs. farro) spinach and artichoke dip, fried chicken and dirty fries and that was just the start! We also had the eggs Benedict, the breakfast croissant and the grilled cheese modified to Loris' recommendation. Everything was tasty and made with love! They were also super dog friendly and made it a pleasant experience even for our fur friend. Overall, a great place for Sunday brunch!

We recently hosted a welcome reception and a rehearsal dinner for my son and now daughter-in-laws' wedding at Coco Bistro. The food was fantastic, the service was exceptional. The manager Loris was a delight to work with, guiding us to just the right food selections. rearranging the restaurant to accommodate the casual environment we were looking to achieve and attending to the smallest detail personally.

Just OK. Although I was initially impressed with the ambience, the rest fell short. This is definitely more of your bottomless brunch place versus actually getting good brunch food.  I judge a place based on if you're getting what you paid for and I would say that's where the restaurant missed the mark. It's a place that is trying to be classy by charging high prices but cutting corners with ugly tablecloth (reveal the beautiful wood tables underneath!!), cheap hand soap and of course average food.  The Brunch Burger was simply two flavorless beef patties with "truffled" brie (almost no truffle in there)  and shoe string fries.  The Eggs Benedict had extremely runny eggs and also average at best.  Left with a bill north of $50 for two average entrees, a Nespresso coffee and tip, we quickly made the decision that this would be on our "'not likely to return" list.
Good service and Nice food. Music in the background is good.
Decent spot for a bottomless brunch. He burger was good and the farro bowl was worth a try.

Loris and the waitstaff of coco are amazing! We had such a great experience will absolutely be back!! We are not the easiest to impress and require a bit more then normal patrons and they catered to us so well! They deserve more then 5 stars.
Excellent French Food and Wine for a reasonable price. Highly recommended.

We googled "French restaurant " and Coco Bistro popped up and was just 3 short blocks from our house. It was perfect for what my wife and I were looking for. Reasonably priced, simple but creative menu, French with a hint of North African. We were not disappointed. The beet hummus was an tasty start, followed by an exquisite rare steak, and capped by a rich chocolate moose cake chased by a fresh pressed  coffee. Highly recommended!
Certainly a spot worth visiting, the food is excellent and well prepared, the cost is fair and it is regularly clean in here. Highly recommended.

Collaborated with Coco Bistro for a tasting menu/wine paring dinner for 26 people under my Instagram alias @wineabrchronicles. I knew from working with Loris, manager, from beginning to end we would be in good hands. Loris and his team beautifully executed a four course tasting menu and wine pairing and seamlessly served all 26 guests in a timely manner. No easy task serving this number of people at one time. From the charcuterie boards to the salmon and ratatouille to the steak frites and macarons for dessert we were in sensorial overload. Each dish delicious and even more enhanced by the wines Loris and I choice to pair.  I have dined here several times prior to this and have always had a wonderful wine and dine experience. Will certainly make this a staple and I know my guests will be returning as well. Thank you Loris and the team at Coco Bistro for making this event a most memorable one. Cheers and see you soon!

I came here for dinner the other night and the restaurant is a very cute French spot, with great ambience, outdoor seating, very friendly staff, and it was relatively quiet and empty for a Monday night. This place is classical French dishes like escargot or cheese and charcuterie plates, as well as mussels and  different types of seafood. I had the seafood salad which was delicious, as well as a duck appetizer, I was very flavorful. The drinks you’re also reasonably price with glasses cost around $10 a glass.

My other friend got the mussels which was not even worth the price of what we paid for. Their menu is really overpriced for the portions they serve. Not the the place to eat if you want a filling meal.

My husband and I were pretty excited to try this new restaurant, but our experience there really reminds me of a good old saying, “never judge a book by its cover”.  When we got to the restaurant, it was pretty full. But we did see a table ready to be cleaned up, so the wait should not be bad. When a tall and charming restaurant staff invited us to wait at the bar and brought us a wine list, we were like, “sure.” We ordered a wine, as two other girls walked in the restaurant. They were standing by the door. You may have guessed it by now, yeah, the two girls got the table we saw before walking in, though they came after us. As I was waving at the restaurant staff for a answer, he was too busy to even notice.  Why this happened was a curious case. Was it because we ordered the drinks, but the girls didn’t? Was it because the girls were young blonde girls? Was it because they were two girls? ... No one will ever know the reason. But if a restaurant is run by picking and choosing their customers based on their staff’s preference, it clearly has business immorality. So sad.

Nope. Swing and a miss. Nice little place. Good drinks. Friendly wait staff. All of that superseded by the most obnoxious manager/owner in the free world. I go in with my wife for a pre cocktail before a show at the Pier. We sit at the couch section where there is an ottoman. The waitress comes over to greet us and I don't even realize my feet are up on the ottoman, so I quickly remove them, fixing my error. The server laughed and told me I WAS allowed to have my feet up, people did it all the time, and please make myself comfortable. I was grateful for this gesture, as was my wife and thanked her for letting us know. Flash forward five minutes later, Mr pretentious blazer wearing manager, comes right over to us with his hands clenched together in a "prayer" like stance and a face like I had just put my hands all over his freshly painted walls, and says, "please remove your feet from our furniture." I quickly do so, as that was his request, and said, "oh I'm sorry, the waitress said..." and before I can finish, he says, "we don't come to YOUR house, and put OUR feet on YOUR furniture." Really? REALLY?! My jaw dropped, as did my wife's. So now, I have just been scolded like a parent to a 5 year old who tried to eat a cookie before dinner, and feel like a complete idiot, so once again, I apologize and as I try to explain again that I thought I had permission,  he completly walks away in my mid sentence,  as if "I'm done with you" and that was that. This is a good part to acknowledge there were about 9 people in the entire place at this time, and some were staff. It was just a real uncomfortable, unfortunate moment that took the wind right out of our evening. The original server came by and said she was sorry for the confusion and that people put their feet up ALL THE TIME,  but the damage was done. To add insult to injury, another group of people came in about 10 minutes later, and it was all warm greetings, hugs and kisses from mr warmth himself, owner/manager. Regulars, I guess. Which is HOW you want to be treated. My wife and I clearly did not make that list. So there you have it, folks. Not cool. Will not be returning. And I will be telling all friends and family as well to avoid like the plague. I'm thinking some readers of this review will roll their eyes and say I am making a big deal, which is your right. But you weren't there, folks. It was humiliating, unnecessary and I wouldn't wish it on anyone looking to have a nice time at a new place. Even if he  had came back, just once,to check on us or converse with us, just to show there were no hard feelings. Nope. Couldn't be bothered. He said what HE needed to say, and ignored us for the duration of our stay. (Which was about 50 minutes....my wife doesn't drink quickly). His ottoman, was more important then the feelings of my wife and me.
Service was ok. Food was not bad either. Pricing could have needed some doctoring though, but overall it was an ok place to eat.

This is probably my worst experience at any restaurant I've visited. I do PR for a restaurant group and travel for culinary experiences as part of work. In any case, we were fine that there was no hostess, so I decided to go to the bar to ask for a table for lunch. I told the bartender that I wanted a drink while I wait for a table ( mind you the restaurant was empty ). The manger approached my guest and I, and told us in order to stay at the bar we must order a drink, which we did, and advised him that we are waiting for a table. He continued to ignore what we said and told us that there was no table for lunch. Meanwhile, a group of tourists walked in grabbed a table themselves and were given menus right away.  I walked out and knowing that I live in the neighbor, I will NEVER go back. I'll be sharing this with all of my neighbors along with any friends that visit to NEVER COME HERE! The food seemed okay to begin with but we wanted to support our local business. Honestly, there are so many better places to dine in the area.

Cute place with outdoor seating available. Lots of table on Sunday evening when I visited.  We were forgotten for 15 minute after we received menu and bread but they come around.  Portion is on the small side so order more than one dish per person.  The Nutella cake was delicious and unique.  Duck confit is deboned duck crusted and pan fried.  It’s quite delicious.  Limited selection on glass of wine, more by bottle. Pasta was good but need higher ratio of meat to pasta.  Overall not a bad place to hit if you are in the area but probably not worth marking a special trip to try.
